	<body>
		<h3>
			Input Encoding
		</h3>
		<p>
			Without exception, a well-formed <span class="lang">mdoc</span> document consists only of <a class="term"
				href="glossary.xhtml#ascii">ASCII</a> printable characters, the space character, the newline character, and in
			some cases the tab character.  Most modern formatters allow for CR+LF newlines <span class="screen">\r\n</span>, but
			this is not portable.
		</p>
		<p>
			Unilaterally, the backslash <span class="screen">\</span> is always interpreted as the beginning of an <a
				href="part2-1-2.xhtml">escape sequence</a>.
		</p>
		<p>
			On text input lines (lines not beginning with a <a class="term" href="glossary.xhtml#mdoc_macro">macro</a>), any ASCII
			character may be used and is considered text.
		</p>
		<p>
			On macro lines, however, the following non-alphanumeric characters are syntactically meaningful as follows.  These
			characters are collectively called reserved characters.
		</p>
		<a name="reserved" />
		<table>
			<col style="width: 5em;" />
			<col />
			<tbody>
				<tr>
					<td><span class="screen">!</span></td>
					<td>punctuation</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><span class="screen">&quot;</span></td>
					<td>control character (quotation)</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><span class="screen">(</span></td>
					<td>punctuation</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><span class="screen">)</span></td>
					<td>punctuation</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><span class="screen">,</span></td>
					<td>punctuation</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><span class="screen">-</span></td>
					<td>control character (macro argument)</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><span class="screen">.</span></td>
					<td>punctuation</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><span class="screen">:</span></td>
					<td>punctuation</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><span class="screen">;</span></td>
					<td>punctuation</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><span class="screen">?</span></td>
					<td>punctuation</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><span class="screen">[</span></td>
					<td>punctuation</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><span class="screen">\</span></td>
					<td>control character (<a href="part2-1-2.xhtml">escape sequence</a>)</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><span class="screen">]</span></td>
					<td>punctuation</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><span class="screen">|</span></td>
					<td>punctuation</td>
				</tr>
			</tbody>
		</table>
		<p>
			To pass these characters along as literal text, you must either escape or quote them.
		</p>
